The paper deals with classic problems in computational geometry, specifically finding coordinate-wise maxima and convex hulls of a planar point set. This suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses self-improving algorithms, which involve learning from inputs and optimizing running time, indicating a possible fit with the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-categories. The paper also mentions new tools for understanding linear comparison trees, which could relate to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the use of expected running time as a metric suggests a possible connection to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
